ashire, England","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT. 1252–1313":"about 1252–1313","1252–1313":"1252–1313","1269–1309":"1269–1309","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1277–Male":"1277–Deceased","1245–1308":"1245–1308","1285–1346":"1285–1346","1225–1285":"1225–1285","1242–1319":"1242–1319","25 March 1285":"25 March 1285","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1271":"1271","1290":"1290","ABT. 1252":"about 1252","1259":"1259","1313":"1313","1225":"1225","1346":"1346","1269":"1269","22 June 1308":"22 June 1308","1245":"1245","1277":"1277","10 June 1285":"10 June 1285","Aft 1285":"after 1285","1309":"1309","1319":"1319","1308":"1308","Scotton, Lincolnshire, England":"Scotton, Lincolnshire, England","Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nevill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Neville","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":7,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":38,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert de Nevill was born about 1252, in Scotton, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Geoffrey de Neville, was 28 and his mother, Margaret Longvillers, was 12. He married Princess Angharad Verch Gruffudd on 10 June 1285. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1313, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"ABT. 1252–1313":"umbes 1252–1313","1252–1313":"1252–1313","1269–1309":"1269–1309","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1277–Male":"1277–Surnud","1245–1308":"1245–1308","1285–1346":"1285–1346","1225–1285":"1225–1285","1242–1319":"1242–1319","25 March 1285":"25. märts 1285","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1271":"1271","1290":"1290","ABT. 1252":"umbes 1252","1259":"1259","1313":"1313","1225":"1225","1346":"1346","1269":"1269","22 June 1308":"22. juuni 1308","1245":"1245","1277":"1277","10 June 1285":"10. juuni 1285","Aft 1285":"pärast 1285","1309":"1309","1319":"1319","1308":"1308","Scotton, Lincolnshire, England":"Scotton, Lincolnshire, England","Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England","Wem, Shropshire, England":"Wem, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT. 1252–1313":"noin 1252–1313","1252–1313":"1252–1313","1269–1309":"1269–1309","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1277–Male":"1277–Kuollut","1245–1308":"1245–1308","1285–1346":"1285–1346","1225–1285":"1225–1285","1242–1319":"1242–1319","25 March 1285":"25. maaliskuuta 1285","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1271":"1271","1290":"1290","ABT. 1252":"noin 1252","1259":"1259","1313":"1313","1225":"1225","1346":"1346","1269":"1269","22 June 1308":"22. kesäkuuta 1308","1245":"1245","1277":"1277","10 June 1285":"10. kesäkuuta 1285","Aft 1285":"1285 jälkeen","1309":"1309","1319":"